    {
      "abstract": "China's drive towards clean energy, especially the expansion of deep-sea offshore wind farms, has highlighted the potential of floating wind turbines. These turbines can effectively harness abundant wind resources and offer flexible deployment options, making them a promising technology. However, they also generate more pronounced wake effects, which challenge traditional wake models and lead to inaccurate power output predictions. Additionally, the inherent volatility of wind power necessitates robust energy storage solutions to stabilize output and enhance the adoption of renewable energy. This study presents an advanced wake model specifically designed for floating wind turbines, significantly improving the accuracy of power forecasts in wind farms. It also introduces a smart operational strategy for a hybrid electricity-hydrogen storage system, utilizing Variational Mode Decomposition (VMD) to optimally distribute stored power. Testing has shown that the new wake model provides predictions that closely match real-world data. Furthermore, the hybrid storage system reduces peak 10-minute power fluctuations from 5.8 MW to 3.9 MW, achieving a 32.76% smoothing effect.",
